1. e4 {The Schilling-Kostic Gambit occurs after black plays 3...Nd4 in response 
to the Italian Game} ({3.Bc4}) {.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {White chooses the 
Italian game. Less positional and more tactical than the Ruy Lopez, and more 
popular at the club level than Ruy as well. White looks to pressure the weak f7 
square immediately and is probably hoping Black will allow the Fried Liver 
attack.} Nd4 {Here we begin the Schilling-Kostic Gambit. White has a few options 
here, but among the most tempting is to accept the gambited pawn, which is 
totally fine, but white can get into trouble fast if care isn't taken or they're 
playing too quickly.} 4. Nxd4 {White plays it safe, going for an even trade and 
doubling Black's pawns on the d-file.} exd4 {Forced to maintain material 
balance.} 5. Qf3 {White pressures f7.} Qf6 {Offering a Queen trade, if White 
accepts Black can take back with the Knight and make a good developing move at 
the same time.} 6. Qxf6 Nxf6 7. d3 {Opening the Bishop and defending the e4 
pawn.} Ng4 8. Nd2 {Getting on with development.} Bc5 9. h3 Ne5 10. Bb5 c6 11. 
Ba4 a5 *

