1. e4 {The Schilling-Kostic Gambit occurs after black plays 3...Nd4 in response 
to the Italian Game} ({3.Bc4}) {.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {White chooses the 
Italian game. Less positional and more tactical than the Ruy Lopez, and more 
popular at the club level than Ruy as well. White looks to pressure the weak f7 
square immediately and is probably hoping Black will allow the Fried Liver 
attack.} Nd4 {Here we begin the Schilling-Kostic Gambit. White has a few options 
here, but among the most tempting is to accept the gambited pawn, which is 
totally fine, but white can get into trouble fast if care isn't taken or they're 
playing too quickly.} 4. c3 {Trying to kick the Knight and possibly prepare 
d2-d4.} Nxf3+ {The only good option for Black here.} 5. Qxf3 {White pressures 
f7.} Qf6 {Offering a Queen trade, if White accepts Black can take back with the 
Knight and make a good developing move at the same time.} 6. Qg3 {White avoids 
trading Queens for now, pressuring e5 and g7 instead.} d6 {Opening the bishop 
and strengthening the pawn on e5.} 7. d3 {Opening the Bishop and defending e4.} 
h5 8. Qe3 Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 10. Qg5 Nf4 11. Bxf4 exf4 12. Qxf6 gxf6 {White has 
managed to triple our pawns on the f-file in this variation. The compensation 
we'll have to play off of is the half-open g-file for our Rook and just try to 
be careful.} 13. Nd2 Rg8 14. Kh1 Be6 {hoping to trade Bishops to un-screw our 
pawns a bit.} 15. a4 O-O-O *

