[Black "Schilling-Kostic Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "01 1.e4"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "trappy-repertoire-for-black-against-1e4-and-1d4/course/1570, variation/62220"]

1. e4 {The Schilling-Kostic Gambit occurs after black plays 3...Nd4 in response 
to the Italian Game} ({3.Bc4}) {.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {White chooses the 
Italian game. Less positional and more tactical than the Ruy Lopez, and more 
popular at the club level than Ruy as well. White looks to pressure the weak f7 
square immediately and is probably hoping Black will allow the Fried Liver 
attack.} Nd4 {Here we begin the Schilling-Kostic Gambit. White has a few options 
here, but among the most tempting is to accept the gambited pawn, which is 
totally fine, but white can get into trouble fast if care isn't taken or they're 
playing too quickly.} 4. Nxe5 {White attempts to refute the gambit, placing a 
lot of pressure on Black's weak f7 square.} Qg5 {Forking the Knight on e5 as 
well as the g2 pawn.} 5. O-O {Getting the King to safety. But leaving the Knight 
en prise.} Qxe5 {Free Knight!} 6. c3 {Kicking the Knight.} Bd6 {Threatening mate 
in one.} 7. g3 Ne6 8. d3 {Building the center. White would ALMOST be playing 
well in this variation if it weren't for being down a Knight for only one pawn, 
and so Black will have to play slightly more conservatively.} Be7 9. Re1 {Lining 
up the Rook against the Queen.} Qf6 10. e5 Qf5 11. d4 {White solidifies his pawn 
chain.} Ng5 {Looking at h3 and f3 for the Knight.} 12. Bxg5 {White doesn't like 
that Knight.} Qxg5 13. f4 {White now has a huge wedge of pawns on the dark 
squares, he has claimed a lot of space that Black doesn't have.} Qf5 14. Nd2 
{Developing.} h5 {Black wants to break up the pawns around White's King. Maybe 
he took a little TOO much space?} 15. Nf1 Qg6 {Pinning the g3 pawn.} 16. Ne3 Kf8 
{Getting the King off the same file as White's Rook.} 17. Qf3 {Keeping Black's 
c7 Bishop in place to defend b7, as well as defending White's pawn on g3.} h4 
{Continuing with the plan.} 18. g4 {White refuses to open the lines around his 
King.} h3 {The far advanced h-pawn is a thorn in White's side from now on.} 19. 
Red1 d6 {Opening the Bishop to threaten g4.} *

