[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "trappy-repertoire-for-black-against-1e4-and-1d4/course/1570, variation/62235"]

1. d4 {White goes for the Queen's pawn game.} Nf6 {The Indian game.} 2. c4 
{Whenever White plays 1.d4, it's a safe bet they'd like their next move to be 
c4, getting two pawns in the center and looking for a Queen's Gambit-ish set 
up.} e5 {The Budapest Defense. Black gambits a pawn on move two. Assuming White 
wants to try refuting the gambit, they'll have to take the pawn.} 3. dxe5 {White 
accepts the gambited pawn.} Ng4 {The Budapest Defense. Threatening to win the 
pawn back with Nxe5. White will most often want to defend the pawn.} 4. Bf4 
{White defends the pawn, either with the Bishop or the Knight to f3, and 
eventually both.} Nc6 {Adding another attacker to e5.} 5. Nf3 {White adds 
another defender to the pawn.} Bb4+ {Black will most likely block with the 
Knight on d2 to preserve his pawn structure. If he blocks on c3, Black can take 
and force white to double their pawns on the c-file.} 6. Nbd2 Qe7 {Black adds 
another attacker to the e5 pawn, and sets up a devious pin.} 7. h3 {This time 
white tries kicking the Knight instead of the bishop. We're still going to take 
on e5 and leave the Knight as bait.} Ncxe5 8. Qb3 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 {White breaks up 
his nice pawn structure to keep the threat on the Bishop and hopes the open 
g-file for his Rook will help compensate for the doubled pawns.} Ne5 10. Bxe5 
Bxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Qxe5 {Getting back the material.} 12. Rg1 {The logical place for 
the Rook.} O-O 13. e3 d6 {Opening the Bishop. Already we can see the difference 
in White's pawns vs Black's.} 14. f4 Qe6 15. c5 dxc5 16. Qc3 {Threatening mate 
in one.} g6 {Defending the mate threat.} 17. Qxc5 Qf6 {Skewering the pawn on g2 
and the Rook behind it on a1.} 18. Qe5 {White offers a Queen trade.} Rd8+ 19. 
Ke2 Qb6 *

