1. d4 {White goes for the Queen's pawn game.} Nf6 {The Indian game.} 2. c4 
{Whenever White plays 1.d4, it's a safe bet they'd like their next move to be 
c4, getting two pawns in the center and looking for a Queen's Gambit-ish set 
up.} e5 {The Budapest Defense. Black gambits a pawn on move two. Assuming White 
wants to try refuting the gambit, they'll have to take the pawn.} 3. dxe5 {White 
accepts the gambited pawn.} Ng4 {Threatening to win the pawn back with Nxe5.} 4. 
Bf4 {White defends the pawn, either with the Bishop or the Knight to f3, and 
eventually both.} Nc6 {Adding another attacker to e5.} 5. Nf3 {White adds 
another defender to the pawn.} Bb4+ {Black will most likely block with the 
Knight on d2 to preserve his pawn structure. If he blocks on c3, Black can take 
and force white to double their pawns on the c-file.} 6. Nbd2 Qe7 {Black adds 
another attacker to the e5 pawn, and sets up a devious pin.} 7. a3 {White tries 
kicking the bishop, but black has...} Ncxe5 {White can't take the Bishop because 
of Nd3#.} 8. Nxe5 {I think this is White's best move here. The end of this line 
is potentially the most even as far as material and having fairly balanced pawn 
structures for both sides. But the potential for danger is still present.} Nxe5 
9. Bxe5 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxe5 11. Rc1 d6 *

