[Comment "trappy-repertoire-for-black-against-1e4-and-1d4/course/1570, variation/62453"]

1. d4 {White goes for the Queen's pawn game.} Nf6 {The Indian game.} 2. c4 
{Whenever White plays 1.d4, it's a safe bet they'd like their next move to be 
c4, getting two pawns in the center and looking for a Queen's Gambit-ish set 
up.} e5 {The Budapest Defense. Black gambits a pawn on move two. Assuming White 
wants to try refuting the gambit, they'll have to take the pawn.} 3. dxe5 {White 
accepts the gambited pawn.} Ng4 {The Budapest Defense. Threatening to win the 
pawn back with Nxe5. White will most often want to defend the pawn.} 4. f4 
{Usually White defends with the Knight or Bishop to develop and defend 
simultaneously, but in these lines White deploys another pawn instead.} Bc5 
{Attacking the vacant f2 square a second time.} 5. e3 {Blocking the attack on 
f2. White's Bishops are looking rather dull being blocked by their own pawns, 
and his development is way behind.} d6 {Opening the Bishop. Black doesn't care 
if White wants to take the pawn to undouble his pawns on the e-file.} 6. exd6 
O-O 7. dxc7 Qxc7 8. Be2 Nxe3 {Free pawn!} 9. Bxe3 Bxe3 {Getting back the 
material.} 10. Nc3 Qxf4 {Another free pawn!} 11. Nf3 {White finally focuses on 
getting developed.} Be6 12. g3 {Trying to get the Queen away.} Qh6 13. Qb3 
{Eyeing Black's pawn on b7} Re8 {Lining up the Rook on the open file against 
White's King.} 14. Qxb7 {White grabs the pawn.} Nd7 15. Rd1 Rab8 *

